@page
@model EfficientLINQ.Pages.IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Efficient LINQ";
}

<section class="hero-card">
    <p class="eyebrow">40-Advanced-EFCore</p>
    <h2>Write LINQ that asks for less</h2>
    <p class="lead">
        This lesson shows how small LINQ choices change SQL shape, network payload, and query cost. The focus is not “clever EF Core”, but clearer requests to PostgreSQL.
    </p>

    <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button-primary" asp-page="/QueryLab/Index">Open Query Lab</a>
        <a class="button-secondary" asp-page="/Products/Index">View Product Page</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="grid-panels">
    <article class="panel">
        <h3>Patterns covered</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Projection instead of full entity loading</li>
            <li>`AsNoTracking` for read-only queries</li>
            <li>Server-side filtering and sorting</li>
            <li>`Skip` and `Take` for paging</li>
            <li>`GroupBy` translation to SQL</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
        <h3>What goes wrong</h3>
        <p>
            Slow pages often start with an innocent `ToListAsync()`, then keep filtering and shaping data in memory. That wastes database bandwidth and makes the application do work the database could do faster.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
        <h3>What students should notice</h3>
        <p>
            The improved query is usually shorter, not longer. It simply asks for the right rows and columns at the right time.
        </p>
    </article>
</section>
